php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Safiya Bukhari","first_name":"Safiya","middle_name":"Asya","last_name":"Bukhari","aka":"Bernice Jones","description":"Safiya Bukhari, born Bernice Jones in The Bronx in 1950, was a member of the New York chapter of the Black Panther Party, a soldier in the Black Liberation Army, and the principal co-founder of the Jericho Movement for amnesty for U.S. political prisoners. She joined the BPP after witnessing New York police harass a Panther selling The Black Panther newspaper on a Harlem street. After the 1971 split that destroyed the BPP as a national organization she went underground with the Black Liberation Army.\n\nShe was arrested in Norfolk, Virginia in January 1975 in connection with a Black Liberation Army attempted robbery and convicted of armed robbery. She was sentenced to a long term in the Virginia state prison system, escaped briefly in 1976, and was recaptured. She served nine years, much of it at the Bedford Hills Correctional Facility for Women in New York after a transfer, before her release in 1983.\n\nWith Jalil Muntaqim and others, she founded the Jericho Movement in 1998 to demand the release of all U.S. political prisoners. She served as its first national chair until her death from a heart attack on August 24, 2003 at age 53. Her collected essays and speeches were published posthumously as The War Before (2010), with a foreword by her daughter Wonda Jones.","state":"New York","race":"Black","gender":"Female","birthdate":"1950-10-24","death_date":"2003-08-24","ideologies":["Black Liberation"],"affiliation":["Black Panther Party","Black Liberation Army","Jericho Movement"],"in_custody":false,"released":true,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Bedford Hills Correctional Facility for Women","institution_state":"New York","charges":"Armed robbery — Black Liberation Army action","arrest_date":"1975-01-25","incarceration_date":"1975-01-25","release_date":"1983-08-24","sentence":"~9 years state prison","convicted":"Yes — Virginia state court, 1975"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Afeni Shakur","first_name":"Afeni","last_name":"Shakur","aka":"Alice Faye Williams","description":"Afeni Shakur, born Alice Faye Williams in Lumberton, North Carolina in 1947, was a leader of the New York chapter of the Black Panther Party and one of the most prominent women defendants of the postwar Black liberation prosecutions. On April 2, 1969, she was arrested with twenty other New York Panthers in the case that became known as the Panther 21 — accused of conspiring to bomb New York police stations, a railroad station, and Manhattan department stores. She was held without bail at the Womens House of Detention in Greenwich Village for eleven months before being released on bond in February 1971. She was pregnant during her detention and gave birth to her son, the rapper Tupac Shakur, on June 16, 1971 — one month after she and the rest of the Panther 21 were acquitted on all 156 counts by a New York jury after a record-long deliberation of less than 45 minutes.\n\nShe represented herself at portions of the Panther 21 trial. After her release she remained politically active for decades, working in legal reform and prisoner support, and after her sons death in 1996 she founded the Tupac Amaru Shakur Foundation. She died on May 2, 2016.","state":"New York","race":"Black","gender":"Female","birthdate":"1947-01-10","death_date":"2016-05-02","ideologies":["Black Liberation"],"affiliation":["Black Panther Party","Panther 21"],"in_custody":false,"released":true,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Womens House of Detention","institution_city":"New York","institution_state":"New York","charges":"Conspiracy to bomb New York City police stations, a railroad station, and Manhattan department stores (Panther 21 prosecution)","arrest_date":"1969-04-02","incarceration_date":"1969-04-02","release_date":"1971-05-13","sentence":"Held without bail approximately 11 months at the Womens House of Detention; bonded out February 1971; acquitted with the entire Panther 21 by New York jury on May 13, 1971 after deliberation of less than 45 minutes","convicted":"No — acquitted on all 156 counts"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Herman Ferguson","first_name":"Herman","last_name":"Ferguson","description":"Herman Ferguson was a New York City public-school principal, a co-founder of the Organization of Afro-American Unity with Malcolm X in 1964, and a longtime leader of the Republic of New Afrika movement. After Malcolm Xs assassination in February 1965, Ferguson became one of the most prominent organizers of the radical Black liberation network that grew out of the OAAU and the Revolutionary Action Movement.\n\nIn June 1967 he was arrested by the New York Police Departments Bureau of Special Services and charged with conspiracy to murder Roy Wilkins of the NAACP and Whitney Young of the National Urban League. The principal evidence at trial came from a paid NYPD informant. Ferguson was convicted in 1968 and sentenced to three and a half to seven years in New York state prison. While free pending appeal he fled the United States with his wife Iyaluua Ferguson and settled in Cooperative Republic of Guyana, where they remained for twenty years. He returned voluntarily to New York in April 1989 and surrendered. He served roughly three years in New York state prison and was released in 1992.\n\nHe spent his last decades organizing for the freedom of U.S. political prisoners, serving as a co-chair of the Jericho Movement and on the board of the Malcolm X Commemoration Committee. He died on October 14, 2014, age 93.","state":"New York","race":"Black","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1921-06-25","death_date":"2014-10-14","ideologies":["Black Liberation","Pan-Africanist"],"affiliation":["Organization of Afro-American Unity","Republic of New Afrika","Revolutionary Action Movement","Jericho Movement","Malcolm X Commemoration Committee"],"in_custody":false,"released":true,"in_exile":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"New York State Department of Corrections","institution_state":"New York","charges":"Conspiracy to murder Roy Wilkins (NAACP) and Whitney Young (National Urban League)","arrest_date":"1967-06-21","incarceration_date":"1989-04-15","release_date":"1992-04-15","sentence":"3.5 to 7 years New York state prison; served 3 years after voluntary 1989 return from 20 years of exile in Guyana","convicted":"Yes — New York state jury verdict, 1968"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Keith LaMar","first_name":"Keith","last_name":"LaMar","aka":"Bomani Shakur","description":"Keith LaMar, who has taken the name Bomani Shakur in prison, is an Ohio death row prisoner whose case is among the most contested wrongful-conviction cases in U.S. capital litigation. He was 19 years old and serving an 18-year sentence for an unrelated 1989 manslaughter when, on April 11, 1993, the Lucasville Prison Uprising began at the Southern Ohio Correctional Facility. Over the eleven days of the uprising one prison guard and nine prisoners were killed. LaMar was charged with five of the prisoner killings and tried by an all-white jury in 1995 in rural Lawrence County, Ohio. He was sentenced to death.\n\nHe has consistently maintained his innocence. The state has never produced any physical evidence connecting him to the killings; the conviction rested entirely on the testimony of incarcerated witnesses, several of whom received reductions in their own sentences in exchange. Years of post-conviction litigation have established that the prosecution failed to disclose statements from other prisoners identifying different killers — Brady violations the federal courts have nonetheless declined to remedy.\n\nHe has spent the past three decades in solitary confinement, almost entirely at the Ohio State Penitentiary supermax in Youngstown. His memoir Condemned: The Whole Story (2014) is widely cited in U.S. carceral writing. His scheduled execution date of January 13, 2027 (rescheduled from 2023 by Governor DeWine) makes him one of the most prominent imprisoned writers in the United States.","state":"Ohio","race":"Black","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1969-08-21","ideologies":["Prison abolition"],"affiliation":["Lucasville Uprising defendants"],"in_custody":true,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Ohio State Penitentiary","institution_city":"Youngstown","institution_state":"Ohio","charges":"Five counts of aggravated murder; conspiracy — connected to the April 1993 Lucasville Prison Uprising at the Southern Ohio Correctional Facility","arrest_date":"1993-04-21","incarceration_date":"1995-08-01","sentence":"Death (currently scheduled for January 13, 2027); plus the original underlying 18-year manslaughter sentence","convicted":"Yes — Lawrence County, Ohio jury verdict, 1995"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Siddique Abdullah Hasan","first_name":"Siddique","middle_name":"Abdullah","last_name":"Hasan","aka":"Carlos Sanders","description":"Siddique Abdullah Hasan, born Carlos Sanders, is an Imam and an Ohio death row prisoner sentenced for his alleged role in the 1993 Lucasville Prison Uprising at the Southern Ohio Correctional Facility. The eleven-day uprising began on April 11, 1993 after escalating tensions between Muslim prisoners and prison administration over forced TB testing that violated Islamic medical practice; one prison guard and nine prisoners were killed. Hasan was charged with the murder of guard Robert Vallandingham and sentenced to death in 1996.\n\nHe has consistently maintained his innocence. He has been a leading spokesperson for the Lucasville defendants in the decades since, and was the central organizer of the 2011 and 2018 hunger strikes by Lucasville death-row prisoners that drew international attention. He has spent the past three decades in solitary confinement at the Ohio State Penitentiary supermax in Youngstown. His scheduled execution date is currently 2027.","state":"Ohio","race":"Black","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1963-01-01","ideologies":["Islam","Prison abolition"],"affiliation":["Lucasville Uprising defendants"],"in_custody":true,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Ohio State Penitentiary","institution_city":"Youngstown","institution_state":"Ohio","charges":"Aggravated murder of corrections officer Robert Vallandingham — connected to the April 1993 Lucasville Prison Uprising","arrest_date":"1993-04-21","incarceration_date":"1996-09-01","sentence":"Death","convicted":"Yes — Ohio state jury verdict, 1996"}]}'

